segments.text: First of all, Mr. Hale, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, and if you remember them or know them, the dates and places of their birth and death, the date and place of your birth, the schools you attended before you came to Texas A&M, and whatever else you can remember about your childhood.
My father and mother, my father's name was William Brewer Hale.
And my mother was from, they were both from Tennessee.
And her name was Alice Mitchell before she married.
And the father came to Texas in 1883 and settled in Coffman County.
The reason he came to Texas, they had a smallpox back there in Jonesboro, Tennessee, and he had an uncle living down here.
The uncle rode him and told him he'd come and see of him until the smallpox rolled.
In those days, you know, smallpox kill you.
They didn't have much way to be treated.
So he came here in 1883 and he liked it and so he stayed.
In 1886 he went back to Tennessee and married this girl Alice Mitchell.
So my mother and father then lived down here in Kauffman County from 1886 to 1900 when he moved out to Swisher County, Tudor, Texas.
There wasn't a railroad there then.
The Litten Years Railroad was at Canyon.
And so we lived on the ranks 28 miles south of Canyon for five years.
And the railroad first came to Tudor in 1906.
So I went, in 1906 then, my dad moved to town so his kids could go to school.
He had four boys and two girls.
And we were seven years old before he'd go to school when I was a kid.
But I skipped one grade, third grade got crowded and they sent three of us to the fourth.
And I had to be one of those three.
So that would make me famous, start school when I was six.
So I got out of school.
I graduated from Tule High School in 1918.
Now you were born what year then?
Born in 1900.
That would be the year your family moved to?
Yeah, I was born in May and they moved in 1901.
In December 1901 to Swish County.
Okay.
And you graduated from Tulia High School in May of 1918 and that's the only school you had gone to in Tulia.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M?
Well the superintendent of the school told us that they had a military program going on here and also an educational program at A&M we could get in both of them because we had to sign up
when we're 18 years old, September the 12th, just a little while before school started here.
And he says, if we come down here, they let us go to school and stay here until March next year.
But he says, if the war was over before then, we'd be gaining a lot by coming here and getting in the SATC and also going to school.
And three of us did that.
It was one of the best things that ever happened to me.
I sure was glad of it.
Of course, we had a hard time that year because of the flu.
There was some regular Army people here besides the students in those days, and counting the regular Army boys and the students too, there was about 80 boys died here that fall.
But I never did have the flu.
You were one of the lucky ones.
Well, the lucky ones never did have the flu, but we had to head down to the hospital and off hours.
because they didn't have enough help.
And then when the war was over, well, we just started regular classwork in school.
We was going to school anyway, but it upset it a little bit, but not too much.
We didn't, we still graduated in time, in four years time, just like it never had happened.
So from that September when you enrolled until January, I believe, when they started kind of a new school year, particularly for those who had been away, you actually attended regular classes.
Yes.
Plus, did you have to do some additional drilling?
Oh, yeah.
You see, we had to do additional drilling and trench digging because that was a trench warfare in World War I.
And we dug a lot of trenches around here.
And did a lot of bandit practice and stuff like that.
And then had a military manual that we studied.
And the army really had a pretty good program.
There's only one thing that was about it.
The officers we had down here had only 90 days training before they came down here.
And every one of the officers named down here began with a K.
Keese, Kennedy, King, and all that came down here from Wisconsin or somewhere.
And they didn't even know how to put us in the mess hall to eat our meals.
We'd go up to the steps, and then they'd say, Squad 1, forward march, and set the table, then Squad 2.
Well, we had some juniors here that were still here in school, and they finally called on them to help them a little bit.
They didn't even know how to hold a tree.
And these juniors got him in line.
They'd been schooled here three years, see.
And it worked out all right.
But if I was, although that flew and we had a lot of misery and all,
If I were going to school at A&M again and could pick my years, I'd pick 18 to 22, just like I had before.
You mentioned the SATC.
Students Army Training Corps.
Otherwise known as Stay Around Till Christmas.
Yeah, or Safe at the College.
I've not heard Safe at the College before.
You haven't heard that one?
No, no.
Dr. Hedges told me that one.
Oh, is that, those are kind of...
Kind of like Aggie Jokes.
Aggie Jokes are, I'm trying to think of the word, names that the students would use.
Oh, yeah.
Students give everybody a name.
You indicated earlier about, say, at the time you graduated from high school, when you reached your 18th year, you had to sign up.
I had to sign up September the 12th.
That is, that everybody who was 18 or more had to register for the draft.
That was the first draft that we'd had in a long time.
I know the North had a draft during the Civil War, which was not very popular.
By that date, everybody who was 18 had to sign up.
That's right, by September the 12th.
Had you had any prior knowledge to what life was like at A&M before you came here?
Well, my mother tried to get me not to come here.
She wanted me to go to Baylor.
And I don't know where she got all this information, but she said they had mosquitoes down here and malaria and said the boys beat on you all the time and just a whole lot of stuff like that.
And so the more she talked, the more I kind of wanted to come down here.
I told her, I said, now, Mom,
They've been telling the boys to graduate down there.
And I said, if they could graduate down there, I can too.
And I talked her into it, and I came on down here.
And she was later glad I came.
But she didn't want me to come down here.
But I went into the 2D high school, had a little library, not very big, but long about that time, about 1918, I guess 1917, they put out a little
brochure or something here entitled 60 Facts About A&M College of Texas.
And you may have it over there in the archives.
Yeah, I have some of those.
But I give mine to old Pink Bounds.
And I thought maybe he put it in the archives.
I think he did.
60 Facts About A&M College of Texas.
And it had a picture of a Hereford cow with a halter on it.
I'd never seen one of those with a halter on it.
We just had range cows out there.
And I kept reading those facts, and they were wonderful, I'll tell you.
I just saw a state highway engineer was from A&M, and an electrical engineer who helped eliminate the Panama Canal, and you never saw so many things in there.
And then in 1913, the sergeant and team from A&M won the contest at International in Chicago, and just things like that, you know.
and what the graduates had done and all.
So that impressed me very much.
I believe that that would still impress high school students if you get out something like that and send these kids to the library.
I don't know where it would not.
Of course, when I was in 1918, that's a long time ago.
Kids are a little different now than they was then.
Well, I think they had some very elaborate
brochures with colored pictures in them that they send out to the high school students nowadays.
What were your first reactions to the school when you arrived?
Well, the first day I spent at A&M was in the rotunda of the, I guess, what do they call that building on the Dome right now?
Academic building.
Academic building, on a cot.
It didn't have the assignments to dormitories and things like that.
And so I spent my first night on a cot in that rotunda of that building.
And when I got up the next morning, they had A&M students, most of them were juniors, assigned
heard these boys around and the various things that they had to do.
And the first thing we did, of course, was go to breakfast.
And I looked at that piece of hull, and I thought that was the biggest thing I ever saw.
And my roommate, his daddy was a rancher.
And when we got to the front door, my roommate says, look at that thing.
And it was big dust.
We were from a little old town, too.
He said, wouldn't this hold a lot of hay?
But I was really, really impressed with A&M College and we thought we had a lot of good buildings in, but man, now, I've been around here so long now, I'm a stranger in my own hometown.
But we had, God Hall was completed that year and Bazell Hall was completed that year and I think Francis Hall was completed that year and
So we thought Gown Hall was just out of this world in those days.
And Brazil Hall, I lived in there three years, sophomore, junior, and senior.
I lived in Leggett and Milner the first two years.
But there were a lot of bedbugs here then and there.
Man alive, you'd come in here after Christmas and turn on your light, and those bedbugs would be climbing all over everywhere.
They'd give you a hard time at night?
Yeah, man, they did.
What did you do to it?
Well, as soon as we'd report the bed bugs, well, they'd get the sulfur out and treat them, you know.
And one time they sent us all to another dormitory, fish, sent us down to Brazel Hall so they could burn that sulfur down there.
And that, I guess, got rid of a lot of them.
Then they'd put these mattresses in a room and treat them, you know.
But I liked A&M from the day I came and the day I left.
It just suited me fine.
Well, you mentioned earlier your mother didn't want you to go because of the story she had heard about hazing.
I don't know where she heard all that.
Did you encounter any?
I didn't hear any of that.
You hadn't heard any?
I hadn't heard any of that.
And it wouldn't have made much difference because I had three brothers older than I.
And...
They hate me all the time anyway.
And for example, and they taught me a lot of things that hit me out down here.
Like, well, my youngest brother was five years older than I was.
When I was about 12, he was 17, and I got me a secondhand little bicycle.
And they were playing down there about a block from where we lived, he and his buddies.
And I went down there on my bicycle.
Well, they didn't want me around because I was too young for them.
So they asked me if I'd, they bragged on my bicycle and then asked me if I'd run them an errand.
And I said, yeah.
And they sent me down to the hardware store to get a can of wrinkles and a half a dozen knot holes.
So I got on the bicycle and I went down there.
Luckily, the owner of the outfit, Mr.
Cancel,
came out there about the time my dad did, and they were good friends, and they knew me ever since I was a baby.
And he put his arm around my shoulder and said, well, I know what I wanted, and I told him I wanted a can of wrinkles and a half-dozen autos.
He knew what, he said, who sent you down here?
And I told him, he said, you tell those boys to come down here themselves and get that.
He saved me, because he's supposed to send me to the next store, you know.
So that kind of stuff was going on down here, you know.
Like they'd send you to Reveille, Fluid,
and all that kind of stuff.
Sell you a ticket to take a bath and stuff like that you didn't need.
Sell you a radiator to heat your room with.
So I just got right into that stuff.
I'd been trained a whole lot by my older brothers.
So the upperclassmen were the ones who would try to sell the fish a ticket to take a bath and a radiator for the room and that sort of stuff.
Yeah.
Were they very successful with some of the other boys?
Well, yes.
And one of the main ones was to pick out some old fish that looked gullible and then promote it to first sergeant and pin it and stuff.
And that fish, he took that seriously.
He tried to tell these other fish
softboard what to do and all that kind of stuff.
They had a lot of fun out of those kind of boys.

Somebody told me about a student who was a fish that was really trying hard in the military and I forget what position they promoted him to but they told him that he was in charge of inspecting all the vehicles that came on campus on Sunday to see if they were carrying any alcohol.
And he stopped Dr. Brazell.
Oh, he did?
And some visiting dignitary and inspected the car.
Isn't that something?
That's really good.
No, I sure did like him.
Of course, everybody was in the cadet corps then, and roomed in the dormitories, and the athletes roomed right with them.
They didn't have any athletic dormitory or anything like that.
And I know when I was a senior, I was a major of the 1st Battalion Infantry.
And I had several football players in the company.
I had two companies, A company and B company.
And Bob Carruthers, who was an outstanding football player, and Peony Wilson.
And those were in there.
And I remember one time, we had to have inspections, and old Peony didn't have his.
the shirt, the emblem on his shirt that he's supposed to have.
And the sergeant major was taking down these things and he'd get the marriage written.
And I said, told him what the thing was.
He said, you mean you're gonna give him the marriage, Peter Williams?
You know, he was out signing football players.
I said, sure.
I said, Peter wouldn't like this if we didn't give him the marriage.
So the world couldn't hear me.
And Puny later thanked me for that.
He says the other kid, they would have forgiven him if he'd got by that.
But we the football players right there in the company with you, you know.
Well, they did have different training tables where they had their own training diets and stuff like that.
But outside of that, they slept in the dormitories with you.
and the drill and all that kind of stuff.
I presume during football season they might miss a drill now and then.
Oh yeah, they relied on it then, yeah.

But we had a class of 19, my fish year, those four years were really, we were very fortunate as far as that is concerned because in 1919 we won the Southwest Conference and wasn't even scored on and made 276 points to nothing.
And we also won the basketball championship along that 19, 19, 20, and 21.
And in 1921, we won another Southwest Conference championship.
And on January the 1st, 22, played the Praying Colonels up there at Dallas Fire and won that game.
And old Peter Wilson, he made the first score.
He recovered a fumble or something behind the goal line and made two points.
But we really had some good athletes, successes in their athletic program when I was here.
I believe the 17 team was the football team.
17, yeah, but I wasn't here.
Yeah, it was also unscored on.
It was, yeah.
And the 19 was unscored.
Yeah, they made 270 points in 1917.
Mm-hmm.
In 19, 19-2, our international livestock, that team won at Chicago.
Mm-hmm.
So we had pretty good four years.
Yeah, yeah.
And now that 22 class really had some wonderful boys in it.
Well, we've got three buildings on the campus named after 22 graduates.
The petroleum building there, Old Music Daugherty, and Zachary Engineering Building, he's a 22 man.
Tom Harrington, 22 man.
So we've got three out of the 22 class.
We've got a building named after Peter.
Yeah, I've been working with the
Mr. Crawford in mechanical engineering.
And he keeps referring to, well, I think particularly 22 and 32 as banner classes.
So many in each of those two classes that have really attained prominence.
They were really prominent classes.
42, I guess.
They were real good boys.
Well, that's the war class.
So many of them, I guess, were killed.
Yes.
Well, if you go backwards from 22, the 12th class had some- Oh yeah, Dutch Horn was in class of 12.
His boy married our eldest daughter.
Dutch Horn, he was a character.
I've read portions of his book, The Dutchman on the Brazos.
He's the one who started selling these tickets to these fish that come off the train down there for 10 cents to take a bath.
Didn't have to buy them, but they didn't know this.
Now Dutch was captain of the football team and baseball team.
The tickets to take a bath would have been for the gnat, I take it.
Yeah, that's right.
What was life like in the dormitory?
I don't believe you've ever... Well, the dormitory life was designed to help the kids so they could study.
In other words, they had to call the quarters.
I forget what it was, about 7, 7.30, 7.30.
And everything had to be quiet because the post had guards in it.
And I guess that's one reason they built these dormitories like Leggett and Milner because you'd walk all around

and they'd inspect every room on every floor and they had in the military they posted the guard and somebody had to walk post once a term and they'd put you on one of these floors and you'd go around and your job was to open the door at 7.30 and ask alright and if they say alright that means nobody's visiting and everybody's there and ought to be there and all that stuff
And everything was quiet and you could study.
And then at 10.30, I believe, or 10.45, they'd give you 15 minutes to get ready to go to bed and blow another bugle.
They used to blow the bugle down here.
And one of the blue taps was 11 o'clock, and he was supposed to be in bed.
And then that old boy would expect again, you see.
Opened the door and said,
Say, all right, your light's supposed to be out, except for seniors.
I think seniors get to leave their light on.
What about at other times during the day?
You know, there was no guard mount then.
No, well, they had an altar of the day.
But that's all.
Well, of course, we had regular army sergeants.
We had artillery and we had...
Calvary, and we had Air Corps, and we had Signal Corps.
We had a lot of division of the Army here then, and it took a lot of regular Army sergeants around here.
We had quite a few of them.
They'd been in the Army, some of them fought down there in Mexico in 1915, along with old Funston and Pershing and a bunch of guys.
And so we had some real good sergeants here that
During the war, they boarded the captain and they had to deal with the mess.
Were they the ones who did the inspections of the rooms?
No, the inspection of the rooms was done by students.
Now, we had to get up and have calisthenics before breakfast when we were going school here.
And then, while we were
our records went to classes while some of the military people inspected our rooms.
And we were supposed to have our beds made, we were supposed to have our shoes shined and all that.
We kept rifles in our room in those days.
And we were supposed to have those rifles cleaned and everything in place.
The rooms were really nice in those days.
Did you ever use the rifles on the rifle range or anything like that or were they just primarily for carrying around?
We did have range practice, yeah.
But they were primarily just for parades.
Where was the rifle range?
It was way back over in there, close to that fish, old fish tank.
I don't know what they call it now.
Back over there where that
Fire School is somewhere in that area.
Uh-huh.
Well, it would be then across the bypass.
Yes.
Then behind there, east, on the other side of Eastwood Airport.
Yeah.
Now, we had an interurban from here to Bryan.
They called it a lot of names.
I don't know what it was.
Jumping Jelly or something.
Tunerville Trolley.
Tunerville Trolley and...
We had no place to go.
There wasn't no such thing as going home on the weekend in those days.
And I never saw a boy get out on the highway and tell me he was riding when I was in school here.
That started later.
You mentioned the interurban to Bryan.
How frequently could you go to Bryan?
Well, you'd have to get a pass to go to Bryan.
And if you wasn't a campus, you'd go nearly any time you want to if you get a pass.
But there wasn't anything to go to except pick show.
And we'd do that sometimes.
And then when you got to be a senior, if you were a captain or higher,
The picture show down there would give you a pass to the show all year long.
And so that was one thing they did for us over in Bryan.
How much did it cost you to ride the trolley to Bryan?
10 cents.
10 cents.
Let's see.
We've talked a little bit about the mess hall.
And you mentioned that your roommate, who was also
West Texas thought it would hold a lot of hay.
I had to agree with you on that.
Yeah, it'd hold even more today.
What was the food like there?
Well, we thought it was good.
Now, every now and then you'd hear a lot of complaints.
And Dr. Brazell was president.
He was president of the CIA before he came down here.
Of course, some of these guys at the CIA don't like to be called that anymore.
makes some of them mad.
Texas University for Women, I believe, what they call it now.
Anyway, Dr. Zell was fed up there and he came down here in 1914.
And he'd hear these complaints about food and so one time he had us all down there in Guyon Hall and those days he'd put everybody in Guyon Hall.
And he had mentioned that and he said now,
you ought to check up a little bit on that and see if you don't weigh more than that.
And you did when you came down here, and usually you would, you know.
But I thought they fed us pretty good.
And they put a pitcher of milk that big on everything.
If you wanted milk, just pour you a glass full, and if you run out, pour another one.
And you had enough to eat.
Some of them might not have liked it, but I thought it was good.
They had pancakes and eggs and bacon for breakfast.
and syrup and stuff like that, and they had cereal.
I don't see how they could beat that.
And sometimes they passed out apples and you could take them home with you or back to your dormitory.
Yeah, some complaints, but I thought it was pretty good.
Well, I imagine there will always be some people who would complain no matter what you feel.
Yeah.
But what did the... We had to learn all these names, us fish did, you know.
Uh-huh.
You mean the special names for the food?
Yeah.
If you didn't ask for it by the right name, you didn't get anything.
That's right.
They call molasses a regulator.
Coffee dope.
I guess that's because of the drug it has in it.
Mm-hmm.
Caffeine.
Caffeine.
Uh-huh.
Uh-huh.
They named them pretty good.
Yes.
Pepper was black.
It was dirt.
Dirt.
Sugar.
Sand, I believe.
No, salt was sand, I believe.
I forget what sugar was.
Bread was gunwale.
Pie was cush.
We never got much.
That's one thing that softball would take away from us sometimes, particularly if it catches us doing something we ought to be, we shouldn't be doing.
And then they'd really take the coach away from us for a week.
Well, it was all kind of home style.
Oh, yeah.
Family style.
You see, each company would be assigned a table, you know, and the same table every time.
So when they march you up the steps and turn you loose, you know where to go.
And you'd get all the food you wanted to eat.
They never did.
Did the upperclassmen ever play any, well, I'll say play games about the food other than taking away your kush?
Well, once in a while you'd hear something like that where they'd add something to it, like I'd put some vinegar on something to make it taste pretty good or something like that, but not very often.
One, I've heard mention of occasional prune races in the mess hall.
Did you ever experience any of those?
No, I didn't.
No?
Okay.
I think some of those things...
